00:00:00.025 --> 00:00:01.400
IGNACIO MONEREO:
So hi, everyone.

00:00:01.400 --> 00:00:02.530
I'm Ignacio, or Nacho.

00:00:02.530 --> 00:00:05.950
I am based in London, and I
work with many game developers

00:00:05.950 --> 00:00:07.720
across the Western
Europe region.

00:00:07.720 --> 00:00:11.470
So many of you-- in fact, I
see a lot of familiar faces.

00:00:11.470 --> 00:00:13.673
So thanks for coming
after the break.

00:00:13.673 --> 00:00:14.590
Thanks for being here.

00:00:14.590 --> 00:00:17.920
And today, we're going to
talk about old games, which

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:20.050
in some cases, in
some instances,

00:00:20.050 --> 00:00:23.120
might be your first success.

00:00:23.120 --> 00:00:26.100
And we are going to
understand whether these,

00:00:26.100 --> 00:00:28.190
they age better or worse.

00:00:28.190 --> 00:00:30.010
And the goal of this
session is basically--

00:00:30.010 --> 00:00:32.220
whoa, that was a
strong introduction.

00:00:32.220 --> 00:00:34.810
So the goal of this
session is essentially

00:00:34.810 --> 00:00:37.130
to understand, what are
the different strategies?

00:00:37.130 --> 00:00:40.480
So if these games are becoming
a burden or a technology debt

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:43.030
or if these are actually
the new opportunity

00:00:43.030 --> 00:00:44.410
that you can actually follow.

00:00:44.410 --> 00:00:47.410
And to do that, I will have on
stage two fantastic speakers,

00:00:47.410 --> 00:00:49.860
so Erik, CEO of
Dodreams, and, as well,

00:00:49.860 --> 00:00:53.470
Anette, VP of Business and
Marketing from Dirtybit.

00:00:53.470 --> 00:00:56.800
So I wanted to start
with a very easy example.

00:00:56.800 --> 00:00:59.230
Because when we're thinking
about old games, then

00:00:59.230 --> 00:01:01.900
I thought, all right,
let's look at old games

00:01:01.900 --> 00:01:03.950
and how they look like today.

00:01:03.950 --> 00:01:06.460
So we have two games
here, both of them

00:01:06.460 --> 00:01:08.820
by the Russian
developer Game Insight.

00:01:08.820 --> 00:01:10.570
I don't know if you're
familiar with them,

00:01:10.570 --> 00:01:14.530
but "Tribez" was published
six years ago in 2012.

00:01:14.530 --> 00:01:18.760
And we have, as well, "Transport
Empire," published in 2014

00:01:18.760 --> 00:01:19.930
four years ago.

00:01:19.930 --> 00:01:22.330
And there is a big difference
among these developers.

00:01:22.330 --> 00:01:23.860
I don't know if
maybe you can guess.

00:01:23.860 --> 00:01:27.690
If you are obviously working for
Game Insights, you would know.

00:01:27.690 --> 00:01:30.230
OK, so I'm just going to--

00:01:30.230 --> 00:01:32.180
so essentially, what
happens with these games

00:01:32.180 --> 00:01:35.300
is that one of these games
is actually a priority today.

00:01:35.300 --> 00:01:38.510
Still it represents a
big part of the revenues.

00:01:38.510 --> 00:01:42.050
So when I was
looking at old games,

00:01:42.050 --> 00:01:45.080
we basically identified that
some of these old games, they

00:01:45.080 --> 00:01:46.880
became an evergreen title.

00:01:46.880 --> 00:01:50.210
And even though it's been a long
time since they were published,

00:01:50.210 --> 00:01:52.730
they still represent a
very important source

00:01:52.730 --> 00:01:54.320
of revenues for the developer.

00:01:54.320 --> 00:01:57.920
And as well, this translates
into having these resources

00:01:57.920 --> 00:01:58.850
into the game.

00:01:58.850 --> 00:02:01.910
And "Transport Empire" would
be part of that back catalog.

00:02:01.910 --> 00:02:04.820
So the first thing to
consider is this one.

00:02:04.820 --> 00:02:07.020
If we look at another
two examples here,

00:02:07.020 --> 00:02:10.009
both of them, in this
case, are top priorities

00:02:10.009 --> 00:02:12.040
for both developers.

00:02:12.040 --> 00:02:14.670
However, if we look
at the right side,

00:02:14.670 --> 00:02:17.450
we might think that this
game is-- it looks classier

00:02:17.450 --> 00:02:19.640
or at least slightly older.

00:02:19.640 --> 00:02:23.630
And in fact, "RuneScape
Old School" by Jagex

00:02:23.630 --> 00:02:27.180
was published in PC for the
first time 17 years ago,

00:02:27.180 --> 00:02:28.160
so it makes sense.

00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:31.190
While "Respawnables,"
Digital Legends,

00:02:31.190 --> 00:02:33.620
was published five
years ago only.

00:02:33.620 --> 00:02:36.470
However, if you are a fan
of "RuneScape Old School,"

00:02:36.470 --> 00:02:39.590
you would know that the game
hasn't been launched yet

00:02:39.590 --> 00:02:40.110
in mobile.

00:02:40.110 --> 00:02:42.830
It's in fact, launching in two
weeks, the 2nd of November.

00:02:42.830 --> 00:02:47.450
So when we are talking
about, why is a game old,

00:02:47.450 --> 00:02:49.100
or how is an old game--

00:02:49.100 --> 00:02:50.450
how do we define these?

00:02:50.450 --> 00:02:52.430
Is it by the launch
date, by when

00:02:52.430 --> 00:02:55.130
the game was released in PC,
in the case of "RuneScape?"

00:02:55.130 --> 00:02:59.640
Or maybe it's just one year,
five years, or two years.

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:02.000
So this is two things that
we need to have in mind,

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:04.910
and then we were trying to
figure out how these games are

00:03:04.910 --> 00:03:07.100
performing nowadays in Play.

00:03:07.100 --> 00:03:09.140
And we had to take
two assumptions, which

00:03:09.140 --> 00:03:10.940
are very big assumptions.

00:03:10.940 --> 00:03:13.943
And the first case was when
the game was published.

00:03:13.943 --> 00:03:15.860
And so we are going to
look at games that were

00:03:15.860 --> 00:03:18.320
published four years or older.

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:20.990
And then also if this game
represents a top priority

00:03:20.990 --> 00:03:21.920
for the company--

00:03:21.920 --> 00:03:24.200
if the game is driving
most of the revenues,

00:03:24.200 --> 00:03:26.580
then in this case, we
will consider an outlier.

00:03:26.580 --> 00:03:29.420
So we're making the
assumption of less than 50%

00:03:29.420 --> 00:03:31.980
of the overall portfolio
of the developer.

00:03:31.980 --> 00:03:35.680
So if we look at these and
we take these into account,

00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:38.510
and we look at the top games
by revenue and downloads

00:03:38.510 --> 00:03:42.380
in the Play Store, we will see
that, in fact, old games are

00:03:42.380 --> 00:03:44.320
very much alive and kicking.

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:46.140
And what it means is that--

00:03:46.140 --> 00:03:48.140
so first of all, old games--

00:03:48.140 --> 00:03:52.520
these games with these four
years old and, as well,

00:03:52.520 --> 00:03:53.570
less than 50%--

00:03:53.570 --> 00:03:56.660
they represent 17%
of those top revenue

00:03:56.660 --> 00:03:58.390
games in the Play Store.

00:03:58.390 --> 00:04:01.490
And as well, they receive
new users every day.

00:04:01.490 --> 00:04:05.470
17.5% of the downloads
in the past six months

00:04:05.470 --> 00:04:07.960
were going to these titles.

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:11.000
From an engagement perspective,
it's something similar.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:12.430
We see that these
old games-- they

00:04:12.430 --> 00:04:15.760
seem to have very engaged
communities and fans that they

00:04:15.760 --> 00:04:20.050
keep playing and, on average,
59% of daily active users

00:04:20.050 --> 00:04:21.692
more than the newer games.

00:04:21.692 --> 00:04:23.650
On the other hand, the
design of the games-- it

00:04:23.650 --> 00:04:27.160
seems to be shorter
[? terms, ?] so shorter times.

00:04:27.160 --> 00:04:28.600
And we see that,
on average, they

00:04:28.600 --> 00:04:33.550
spend less time per daily
active users, so 29% less.

00:04:33.550 --> 00:04:35.590
Also, we take into
account monetization,

00:04:35.590 --> 00:04:36.490
within-app purchases.

00:04:36.490 --> 00:04:38.980
In particular, we will
see that old games,

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:41.600
they tend to monetize
slightly less better.

00:04:41.600 --> 00:04:44.500
And we see minus 18% in ARPDAU.

00:04:44.500 --> 00:04:48.190
And last but not least, as
everything old in this life,

00:04:48.190 --> 00:04:49.720
it tends to have some issues.

00:04:49.720 --> 00:04:52.340
We see that, also, from
a vitals perspective,

00:04:52.340 --> 00:04:58.720
they have, on average, 50% more
crash rates and 20% more ANRs.

00:04:58.720 --> 00:05:03.430
So in a nutshell, these games,
these four-year-old games,

00:05:03.430 --> 00:05:06.730
they have a lot of
new fresh installs,

00:05:06.730 --> 00:05:08.380
new users coming every day.

00:05:08.380 --> 00:05:10.990
They still make a lot
of significant revenue,

00:05:10.990 --> 00:05:13.000
although might be
slightly lower.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.350
And they have some issues
in terms of, for example,

00:05:17.350 --> 00:05:19.680
vitals and crash rates and ANRs.

00:05:19.680 --> 00:05:22.810
Now, the question here
is, is this a burden?

00:05:22.810 --> 00:05:25.360
Do we consider these
games as technology debt,

00:05:25.360 --> 00:05:27.870
or do we consider
it an opportunity?

00:05:27.870 --> 00:05:30.560
And so there's two
very clear ways,

00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:32.320
but there is three routes.

00:05:32.320 --> 00:05:35.810
So there's three common ways
that developers are following.

00:05:35.810 --> 00:05:40.120
So if you go to the very much
I consider this as a burden,

00:05:40.120 --> 00:05:42.735
the ultimate case is
to unpublish the game.

00:05:42.735 --> 00:05:44.110
And this is the
case that we will

00:05:44.110 --> 00:05:45.880
hear from Dirtybit later on.

00:05:45.880 --> 00:05:47.560
If you go on the
other hand, I consider

00:05:47.560 --> 00:05:50.460
this as my biggest
opportunity, then why not

00:05:50.460 --> 00:05:53.980
I put more resources into
this game and try to revamp it

00:05:53.980 --> 00:05:57.290
and become again one of
my top drivers of revenue?

00:05:57.290 --> 00:06:00.610
And this is the case
from Dodreams later on.

00:06:00.610 --> 00:06:04.180
And when we ask developers, we
found out that majority of you,

00:06:04.180 --> 00:06:07.360
that you go into what we
call the back catalog mode

00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:09.980
or long tail or status quo.

00:06:09.980 --> 00:06:14.330
And so we ask, how do
games end up in this mode?

00:06:14.330 --> 00:06:16.690
So there's a couple
of common factors.

00:06:16.690 --> 00:06:20.320
So many times, we see that
LiveOps, new content updates--

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:22.000
they don't have the same effect.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:25.090
As well, the ROI campaigns,
they try to stabilize.

00:06:25.090 --> 00:06:27.670
LTV is very similar to CPIs.

00:06:27.670 --> 00:06:29.500
Other factors could
be also affecting,

00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:32.500
for example, cannibalization
between your own games.

00:06:32.500 --> 00:06:35.140
You launch a new game,
and you see a lot of users

00:06:35.140 --> 00:06:37.470
from the previous one
go into this title

00:06:37.470 --> 00:06:40.060
and, as well, external
factors, such as competitors

00:06:40.060 --> 00:06:42.290
or new genres that
are appearing.

00:06:42.290 --> 00:06:44.860
And does this mean
that the game is dead?

00:06:44.860 --> 00:06:47.200
Well actually, no,
and that's for sure.

00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:49.840
We still have very
engaged communities.

00:06:49.840 --> 00:06:52.900
And as Game Insights
was sharing with us,

00:06:52.900 --> 00:06:55.330
brand perception is very
important, and keeping alive

00:06:55.330 --> 00:06:57.640
this game is critical for them.

00:06:57.640 --> 00:07:00.687
But also, generally,
they're very profitable.

00:07:00.687 --> 00:07:02.770
So if we look at the games
[? instance ?] as well,

00:07:02.770 --> 00:07:05.140
we see that old games,
or long-tail games,

00:07:05.140 --> 00:07:07.810
generate 14% of
the total revenues.

00:07:07.810 --> 00:07:10.810
And on average, they
have 50% more profits

00:07:10.810 --> 00:07:13.190
than the newer ones.

00:07:13.190 --> 00:07:15.670
So what are the key challenges?

00:07:15.670 --> 00:07:17.170
So I put three key challenges.

00:07:17.170 --> 00:07:18.260
There might be more.

00:07:18.260 --> 00:07:21.160
But the main ones would be
first is spaghetti code.

00:07:21.160 --> 00:07:22.790
So some problems with
the-- as the case

00:07:22.790 --> 00:07:26.560
we've seen that they have some
issues with technical problems

00:07:26.560 --> 00:07:28.480
like ANRs and crash rates.

00:07:28.480 --> 00:07:31.120
Also as well, monetization
is hard to keep up

00:07:31.120 --> 00:07:34.340
with the [? CPNs ?] updating
the mediation platforms as well.

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:36.370
Sometimes you might
see that your game

00:07:36.370 --> 00:07:38.440
is using agencies that
they do not [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:38.440 --> 00:07:40.210
or networks that
they are not anymore.

00:07:40.210 --> 00:07:41.860
And last, team.

00:07:41.860 --> 00:07:43.450
Every developer
is looking forward

00:07:43.450 --> 00:07:46.480
to work in the next title,
in the next big hit.

00:07:46.480 --> 00:07:49.960
And convincing then, motivating
the users or the developers

00:07:49.960 --> 00:07:53.400
to actually work in these
games might be hard.

00:07:53.400 --> 00:07:58.680
So just to finalize this,
some very few recommendations

00:07:58.680 --> 00:08:03.960
from another developer here
today with us, Oh BiBi.

00:08:03.960 --> 00:08:06.780
So we have-- to tackle
these precise challenges,

00:08:06.780 --> 00:08:09.960
we can think about the ways
to optimize a target SDK,

00:08:09.960 --> 00:08:12.780
how we can keep updating
the game or the versions

00:08:12.780 --> 00:08:16.860
of the engine in a efficient
way, maybe outsourcing.

00:08:16.860 --> 00:08:18.750
Another way, also,
of thinking is,

00:08:18.750 --> 00:08:21.240
how do we keep an
efficient monetization

00:08:21.240 --> 00:08:24.300
by updating automatically
the CPMs or by,

00:08:24.300 --> 00:08:26.880
for example, automatizing
the customer support

00:08:26.880 --> 00:08:30.580
whenever the players are
using in-app purchases?

00:08:30.580 --> 00:08:34.350
Another very interesting
example, automatizing LiveOps.

00:08:34.350 --> 00:08:38.220
So for example, the Halloween
sales or the Halloween LiveOps

00:08:38.220 --> 00:08:39.780
that you are running
this year might

00:08:39.780 --> 00:08:41.730
be the same as the last year.

00:08:41.730 --> 00:08:43.530
But users, they might not know.

00:08:43.530 --> 00:08:46.140
The players might not know
that this is exactly the same,

00:08:46.140 --> 00:08:48.600
and that keeps the
game fresh and alive.

00:08:48.600 --> 00:08:51.510
And last but not least, we've
seen today a number of examples

00:08:51.510 --> 00:08:55.890
of how can you improve your
conversion via store listings,

00:08:55.890 --> 00:08:57.610
for example, country targeting.

00:08:57.610 --> 00:08:58.590
We have it now.

00:08:58.590 --> 00:09:01.500
And this will help you to
drive and continue driving

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:03.270
those users to your game.

00:09:03.270 --> 00:09:05.580
And with this, I would
like to invite to the stage

00:09:05.580 --> 00:09:07.830
Anette Staloy, who
is going to talk

00:09:07.830 --> 00:09:11.040
about a different way,
which is, in this case,

00:09:11.040 --> 00:09:12.454
to actually go unpublishing.

00:09:12.454 --> 00:09:13.496
ANETTE STALOY: Thank you.

00:09:13.496 --> 00:09:14.975
IGNACIO MONEREO: You're welcome.

